  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT132-kilavi">kaḻaṟṟetirmaṟai.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Rejection [of the companion's] criticism.</p>
          </div>


        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT132">
<l>                kavavukkaṭuṅ kuraiyaḷ kāmar vaṉappiṉaḷ</l>
<l>                kuvavumeṉ mulaiyaḷ koṭikkūn talaḷē</l>
<l>                yāṅkumaṟan tamaikō yāṉē ñāṅkark</l>
<l>                kaṭuñcurai nallā ṉaṭuṅkutalaik kuḻavi</l>
<l>                tāykāṇ viruppi ṉaṉṉa</l>
<l>                cāaynōk kiṉaḷē māa yōḷē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
           <l>
            <choice>
                <seg>She who cries out<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">kurai</term> is given by DEDR 1796 either as a verb, "to bark, jubilate, shout", or as noun, "noise, roar, shout". Here <term xml:lang="ta">kuraiyaḷ</term> quite obviously might be an pronominal noun, perhaps, in accordance with the context, rather jubilating than shouting. Tradition rather tunes down this quite overt statement by taking <term xml:lang="ta">-kurai-</term> as an expletive infix, coming thus to <term xml:lang="ta">kavavu kaṭuṅ(kuraiy)aḷ</term>, "she who is quick to embrace". In accordance with this, <term xml:lang="ta">cāay</term> is taken by TVG as a qualifier in the sense of "she who gives glances out of half-closed eyes". In this case also <term xml:lang="ta">ñāṅkar</term> will not be understood temporally, but rather spatially, meaning something like "to one side".</note> loudly in lovemaking,</seg>
                <seg>She who is quick to embrace,</seg>
            </choice>
            who is beautiful in desire
           </l>
           <l>she with full, soft breasts, she with creeper hair,</l>
           <l>how can I be content to forget [her]?<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">maṟantu amaiku</term>: see note on KT 92.5. Here too the auxiliary function is close at hand, in the sense of a permanent conclusion: "How can I permanently forget [her] ...?"</note>Afterwards,</l>
           <l rend="indent">like, with longing to see [its] mother,</l>
           <l rend="indent">the calf with trembling head of the good cow<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nallāṉ</term>, "good cow" here obviously means "milk cow", that is, the cow that is fit for giving milk.</note> with quick udder,</l>
           <l>
            <choice>
                <seg>she looked [at me]<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">nōkkiṉaḷ</term>: the sense of the p.a. is here once again situative, and supposedly qualified by the adverb <term xml:lang="ta">ñāṅkar</term> "afterwards", namely after lovemaking.</note> exhaustedly, the dark one.<note place="foot">Beautiful the play on <term xml:lang="ta">cāay</term> ... <term xml:lang="ta">māayōḷ</term>. There are reverberations of the second root <term xml:lang="ta">cāy</term> "to emaciate", a process connected with arising pallor. She is called <term xml:lang="ta">māayōḷ</term>, "the dark one", here, because she was like that when he departed, but presumably it could not last.</note></seg>
                <seg>she gives glances out of half-closed eyes, the black one.</seg>
            </choice>
           </l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
